I’ve always worn my heart on my sleeve 💖

My mom calls me her heart. She showed me what unconditional love looks like, what a home feels like, how to practice patience, optimism, and selflessness. 

Right before the pandemic she was diagnosed with Alzheimer’s. I lived with her and took care of her during that time. The hardest part is the feeling of losing her, losing all the things she taught me.

But they’re not lost, they live inside me. The very things she taught me and the way she lived her life are the things I need to care for her. Patience, unconditional love, selflessness. All the things I got from her. 

This tattoo is a reminder, that even in the darkest moments she’s still there. Both my tattoos that represent my parents have flowers in them, reminding me to find beauty in spite of all the pain, and in fact, finding beauty IN the pain which is a constant process. 

I can’t wait to get the rest done next week. Thanks to the incredible @fidelitytattooco for this work of art.

Story time! 

Today I was coaching a client on weighted push-ups. We do sets of 5 and after about 15 he was looking discouraged so I asked what was up.

“I feel like I should be able to do more of these”
I thought for a moment and replied,

“That’s a story.”

Is there some list somewhere that tells you how many push-ups you SHOULD be able to do? 
Did it come from me? His coach? Of course not, he’s doing exactly as many as he’s been programmed
Is he comparing himself to the journey of other people who have been working out longer? 
Absolutely

Everyone has a different fitness journey. The number of reps you SHOULD do is the amount that challenges you while using good form and slowly increases the weight or reps overtime. 

It’s a cliche phrase but the only person you should be comparing yourself to is the person you were yesterday. 

It doesn’t matter if you can only do 5 push-ups. Do five pushups, then when you get stronger do 6, then 7 and someday you’ll be able to do 100.

May you get a little stronger everyday ✨💪🏻✨

Todays mantra: What’s meant to happen will happen and what doesn’t happen wasn’t meant for you.

I used to think I had to work so hard. To get people to like me, to get ahead in my career. I was constantly worried about whether I was doing enough, felt burned out, and inadequate.

I’m slowly learning that the people who are meant to be in your life will work just as hard as you are. The work that really fuels you won’t feel like work. The hardest thing to learn but the thing I’m trying my best to remember is that if it didn’t happen, it wasn’t meant for you.

No matter how much you want something, that new job, the boy you’ve been chasing, the friends you keep trying to get to like you, if it doesn’t happen it means it wasn’t meant for you. Most of the time it has nothing to do with you! I’m learning that despite my vivid imagination of how I want my life to look, sometimes the universe’s plan is far better than any I could have imagined. 

It’s hard to let go of that thing you want but can’t have. But the sooner you let go of the things that aren’t meant for you the sooner you make space for all the incredible gifts that ARE meant for you. 

Still learning, one day at a time 
✨🫀✨

🎶It’s my party and I’ll cry if I want to🎶

I got home last night and noticed my makeup was running from all the crying I’d been doing on the dancefloor

That’s exactly how I want it 

The dancefloor is where I process everything in my life. It’s where I celebrate my victories, embody gratitude, and connect with friends but it’s also a place where I work through the challenges in my life. I’ve worked through grief, anger, sadness, all of it. 

My goal in this life is to feel everything as fully as I can. The joy as well as the grief. There are no “bad” emotions. It’s all part of the human experience. Tears means it mattered, it was important. My only wish is that I can create spaces where people feel safe. It’s the goal of my life, to help other people find the same sense of belonging and purpose that I’ve found dancing. 

Let’s heal our shit, help each other, and have a fucking blast doing it.

Thanks for dancing with me last night dad. I love and miss you 🧭🫀

I look back on the broken pieces of my past and see that those pieces came together to form the disco ball that is my life right now. When I tell people about my silent disco a response I get a lot is “I can’t dance” and here’s my honest answer:

I don’t care.

I don’t care if you have two left feet, I don’t care if you have no rhythm, I don’t care if you look like a dying sea anemone when you dance. 

And neither should you. 

When you’re in an environment that feels safe, surrounded by supportive people, you won’t care what other people think of your dancing. 

This isn’t a normal club, this is a magical little bubble where you’re safe to be silly, to be a shitty dancer, to have fun and no one is going to judge you. When’s the last time you were in a space like that? 

So when someone says “I can’t dance” I say “Good! Come anyway.”

I want the shitty dancers because I want to show you that it’s safe and fun to be yourself. Your self worth has nothing to do with your dancing abilities, and in time you’ll learn that the more of YOU you bring, the more you’ll be celebrated. 

Shitty dancer Pride! Drop a 💃 below if you think you can’t dance, let’s fill the dancefloor with brave shitty dancers!

In times of crisis it’s pretty natural to feel guilty for having fun when there are people in the world suffering and fighting for their lives. How can I have fun at a time like this? 

But I think that’s when it’s most important. 

I’ve come to realize that dancing isn’t just an escape from your everyday life, it’s a vital healing process. 

You come together with your community and for just one night you get to leave the cares of the world at the door. You get to focus on you, shake the stress off, process your emotions, and SWEAT! You leave feeling refreshed, feeling recharged, and resourced. THATS the you that we need! 

We need you at your best. We need your kindness, your heart, your humanity, and you can’t give that if you’re burned out. If you’re recharged you can use that energy to help your community and that’s what we need right now. 

Take care of yourself, take care of your community, and come dance with me. I would be honored to help share your burden for one night. ✨🫀✨

It’s my birthday! I’ve learned so much this year so I wanted to share fifteen of my favorite lessons

-There is not a single aspect of my life that has not been improved by asking myself the question “How can I bring more of myself to this experience?”
-The biggest lie the world tries to make you believe is that you’re alone. It’s our biggest fear and most things in Western society encourage you to be an individual but the truth is we’re all connected. We come from the same source and we need each other to grow and heal
- I unintentionally isolated myself after my dad passed, I’m finally letting my walls down
- Nothing in the universe has an inherent meaning, we as humans, assign meaning to everything, you have more power deciding what your meaning will be than you think 
- Mindfulness has changed my life 
- Learning about my nervous system and how to regulate it has completely changed my relationship with anxiety
- The body, your gut, your intuition, is never wrong
- There is nothing more powerful in a conversation than a good question 
- People tell you who they are with their actions, not their words
- It’s ok to ask for help
- My value is not wrapped up in how good I am or how I look
-An event going well has more to do with me BEing
-I’m not responsible for other people’s emotions 
-I love being a leader, I love inspiring people, I love making a difference 
-The only way to let a feeling go is to feel it as completely as possible 

Here’s to another year of being human, being, being imperfect, and learning even more! 
✨🫀✨

Trauma is stored in the body 

It’s your body’s way of saying “this is too much, let’s save this for later” but most of the time there is no later, it stays stuck inside you, weighing you down, lashing out when you least expect it.

Over the weekend I was in a really good place, I’d been meditating a lot and being really in touch with my body and Saturday night I started thinking about my mom who has Alzheimer’s. I’ve been her caregiver for years but now she lives at an assisted living home and I’ve never really processed the feelings I have around it. It’s just too big, too painful. My entire life became built around protecting me from feeling the weight of the sadness around my moms condition.

But finally that night I felt safe to go there. I sobbed, i WAILED, my body contorted and it felt like I was crying from these knots of tension in my back. I can only imagine what my upstairs neighbors thought. I realized that it’s safe to feel all my feelings. Nothing bad is going to happen, no matter what comes up, I’m going to be ok. The floodgates opened and I continued sobbing. 

Once I was done I started giggling uncontrollably, I couldn’t stop! I continued to dance in gratitude. Gratitude for this life, for the teachers I’ve had recently, for FINALLY cultivating enough safety in my body that I could feel the feelings that have been trapped in my body for who knows how long.

Today I woke up early, felt refreshed, light, and I’m so excited to face the day. My takeaway is that I want to help other people find this same peace. Let’s heal our shit, dance it out, and LIVE! 
✨🫀✨
